lbum [[Blue Valentine (album)|Blue Valentine]] with a cover of this song.\n* [[Ben Platt (actor)|Ben Platt]] performed this song at the [[60th Annual Grammy Awards]] as a tribute to [[Leonard Bernstein]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/3061539/ben-platt-grammy-performance-somewhere/ |title=Ben Platt Goes From Pitch Perfect To Grammy Standing Ovation With Emotional Performance |last=Bell |first=Crystal |date=January 29, 2018 |website=[[MTV]] |publisher= |access-date=August 19, 2018 |quote=}}</ref>\n==New York City Subway==\n[[New York City Subway]] cars have a device that converts the [[direct current]] electricity from the tracks into [[alternating current]] electricity for the cars. This conversion emits three high pitched sounds that are identical to the first three notes of the song. <ref>https://www.wnycstudios.org/story/asking-another-friend</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|barbra-streisand|somewhere}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{West Side Story}}\n{{Leonard Bernstein}}\n{{We Five}}\n{{Barbra Streisand songs}}\n{{Phil Collins songs}}\n{{Pet Shop Boys singles}}\n{{Tom Waits}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Somewhere (song)}}\n[[Category:1956 songs]]\n[[Category:1964 singles]]\n[[Category:1985 singles]]\n[[Category:1996 singles]]\n[[Category:1997 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Stephen Sondheim]]\n[[Category:Songs with music by Leonard Bernstein]]\n[[Category:The Supremes songs]]\n[[Category:Barbra Streisand songs]]\n[[Category:Phil Collins songs]]\n[[Category:Pet Shop Boys songs]]\n[[Category:Aretha Franklin songs]]\n[[Category:Bobby Darin songs]]\n[[Category:Celtic Woman songs]]\n[[Category:Sissel Kyrkjeb\u00f8 songs]]\n[[Category:Devo songs]]\n[[Category:Johnny Mathis songs]]\n[[Category:Crazy Elephant songs]]\n[[Category:Glen Campbell songs]]\n[[Category:Marianne Faithfull songs]]\n[[Category:Rick Astley songs]]\n[[Category:We Five songs]]\n[[Category:Andy Williams songs]]\n[[Category:Songs from West Side Story]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocalist(s)]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the song from West Side Story|other uses|Somewhere (disambiguation){{!}}Somewhere}}\n{{refimprove|date=October 2014}}\n\"'''Somewhere'''\", sometimes referred to as \"'''Somewhere (There's a Place for Us)'''\" or simply \"'''There's a Place for Us'''\", is a song from the 1957 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] [[musical theatre|musical]] ''[[West Side Story (musical)|West Side Story]]'' that was made into [[West Side Story (1961 film)|a film in 1961]]. The music is composed by [[Leonard Bernstein]] with lyrics by [[Stephen Sondheim]], and takes a phrase from the slow movement of [[Piano Concerto No. 5 (Beethoven)|Beethoven's 'Emperor' Piano Concerto]], which forms the start of the melody.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Alex|title=The Rest is Noise: Listening to the Twentieth Century|publisher=Fourth Estate|isbn=978-1-84115-475-6}}</ref> and also a longer phrase from the main theme of [[Pyotr Tchaikovsky]]'s [[Swan Lake]].\n\n==The song in the stage musical==\nIn the [[West Side Story (musical)|stage musical]], the song appears in the second act of the show during the Somewhere Ballet. It is performed by an off-stage soprano singer and is later reprised by the entire company. In the original Broadway production, \"Somewhere\" was sung by [[Reri Grist]] who played the role of Consuelo.\n\nAt the end of the show, when Tony is shot, Maria sings the first few lines of the song as he dies in her arms.\n\nIn late 1957, this recording was released on the album ''[[West Side Story (Original Broadway Cast)]]''.\n\n==The song in the 1961 film==\nIn the [[West Side Story (1961 film)|1961 film]], the song occurs at a pivotal point, after the rumble in which Tony ([[Richard Beymer]]) has stabbed Maria's brother, Bernardo ([[George Chakiris]]). Having nowhere else to go, Tony runs to Maria ([[Natalie Wood]]), who has just been told of her brother's death and who killed him. When Tony comes to her room through the balcony window, Maria, in shock, pounds against his chest.\n\nRealizing in spite of her anger that she still loves Tony, Maria begs him to hold her. After Maria cries out, \"It's not us...it's everything around us.\" Tony replies, \"Then I'll take you away, where nothing can get to us.\" He then begins singing \"Somewhere\" to her. His comforting voice draws her in and it becomes a duet of hope that their love will survive \"somehow, someday, somewhere.\"\n\nAs in the stage show, Maria sings the first few lines of the song as Tony dies in her arms. In 2004, this version finished at #20 on [[AFI's 100 Years...100 Songs]] survey of top tunes in American cinema.\n\n\"Somewhere\" is the only track that is out of sequence on the [[West Side Story (soundtrack)|original soundtrack album]] as it is the last track on Side 2. This is rectified on the CD as \"Somewhere\" is correctly placed in sequence to the film between \"The Rumble\" and \"Cool.\"\n\n==P. J. Proby version==\nIn 1964, [[P. J. Proby]] released his version of \"Somewhere\", which reached number 6 on the British singles chart and 7 on the Australian singles chart. The song also charted well in various European countries.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart positions \n!align=\"left\"|Peak <br>position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[UK Singles Chart]]\n|align=\"center\"|6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[ARIA Charts|Australian Singles Chart]]\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|}\n\n==The Supremes' version==\nIn 1965, [[the Supremes]] recorded the song for their album, ''[[There's a Place for Us]]'', though it went unreleased until 2004. They also used it for their debut appearance at the [[Copacabana (nightclub)|Copacabana]] nightclub in New York City and it eventually became a fixture of their nightclub acts. They also sang the song on ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' and ''[[The Hollywood Palace]]''. In contrast to the original melody, a special dramatic monologue was incorporated, which was frequently changed in conjunction with changes in the group as well as the country's turmoil in the late 1960s.\n\nIn the aftermath of the shooting of [[Martin Luther King, Jr.]], the monologue was changed to reflect King's famous \"I Have a Dream\" speech. When the Supremes appeared on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Johnny Carson]]'' the day after King had been murdered, lead singer [[Diana Ross]] was so overcome with emotion that she practically stumbled through the speech, but got an extraordinary ovation from the studio audience. It would once again be nationally televised several months later that year when the group paired up with [[the Temptations]] for an NBC television special, ''[[TCB (television special)|TCB]]''. The monologue for that special went as follows:<ref>{{cite web |title=The Supremes - Somewhere on Tonight Show (Audio Only) |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5ZSOrQJbcRg |website=YouTube |publisher= |date=November 15, 2014}}</ref>\n\n'' \"Yes, there's a place for each of us,\n'' And we must try to pursue this place.\n'' Where love is like a passion, that burns like a fire,\n'' Let our efforts be as determined as that of Dr. Martin Luther King,\n'' Who had a dream that all God's children,\n'' Black men, white men, Jews, Gentiles, Protestants, and Catholics,\n'' Will join hands and sing that spiritual of all:\n'' \"Free at last! Great God, we are free at last!\" ''\n\n==Barbra Streisand version==\nIn 1985, [[Barbra Streisand]] released a version of \"Somewhere\" as a single off the [[Grammy Award]]-winning ''[[The Broadway Album]]''. In the US, it narrowly missed the Top 40 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]], peaking at number 43, but fared better on the [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|AC]], peaking at number 5. It was a dissapointment in the UK, peaking at number 88.<ref>[http://barbra-archives.com/record/albums/broadway_album.html Barbra Streisand Archives: Records/The Broadway Album.]</ref> The song itself won the [[Grammy Award for Best Instrumental Arrangement Accompanying Vocal(s)]]. In 2011, a duet was produced using scenes from Streisand's version while [[Jackie Evancho]] performed live with David Foster at the [[Ringling Museum of Art]]. On her 2014 ''[[Partners (Barbra Streisand album)|Partners]]'' album, she released a new recording of the song, this time as a duet with [[Josh Groban]].\n\n==Phil Collins version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Somewhere\n| cover      = Somewhere Phil Collins.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Phil Collins]]\n| album      = The Songs of West Side Story\n| released   = [[1996 in music|1996]]\n| format     = [[CD single|CD]], [[12-inch single|12\"]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=02}}\n| label      = [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]], [[Virgin Records|Virgin]], [[Warner Music Group|WEA]]\n| writer     = [[Leonard Bernstein]], [[Stephen Sondheim]]\n| producer   = Phil Collins\n| prev_title = [[We Wait and We Wonder]]\n| prev_year  = 1994\n| next_title = [[Dance into the Light (song)|Dance into the Light]]\n| next_year  = 1996\n}}\n\nBritish drummer [[Phil Collins]] later covered the song in 1996 for the ''[[West Side Story]]'' cover album ''The Songs of West Side Story''.\n\n===Charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1996)\n!align=\"center\"|Peak <br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian Singles Chart \n|align=\"center\"|68\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Hot Adult Contemporary Tracks]]\n|align=\"center\"|7\n|-\n|}\n\n==Pet Shop Boys version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Somewhere\n| cover      = SomewherePSB.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Pet Shop Boys]]\n| album      = [[Bilingual (album)|Bilingual Special Edition]]\n| A-side     = \"[[A Red Letter Day]]\" (US)\n| B-side     = \"The View from Your Balcony\", \"Disco Potential\"\n| released   = 23 June 1997\n| format     = [[CD single]], [[12-inch single|12\"]], [[cassette single]]\n| recorded   = 1995\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Hi-NRG]]<ref>{{cite news|first= Will |last= Dean |url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/music-review-pet-shop-boys-bring-cornucopia-of-hits-to-londons-o2-arena-8664877.html |title= Music review: Pet Shop Boys bring cornucopia of hits to London's O2 Arena |newspaper= [[The Independent]] |date= June 19, 2013 |accessdate= March 31, 2015}}</ref>\n| length     = {{Duration|m=4|s=42}} <br> 10:56 (extended version)\n| label      = [[Parlophone]] / [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]]\n| writer     = [[Leonard Bernstein]], [[Stephen Sondheim]]\n| producer   = Pet Shop Boys\n| prev_title = [[A Red Letter Day]]\n| prev_year  = 1997\n| next_title = [[I Don't Know What You Want But I Can't Give It Any More]]\n| next_year  = 1999\n}}\n\"Somewhere\" was released as a single by the British music group [[Pet Shop Boys]] on 23 June 1997 to promote their \"Somewhere\" residency at the [[Savoy Theatre]] in London, which was named after the song, and to promote a repackage of ''[[Bilingual (album)|Bilingual]]''.\n\nThe single was another top 10 hit for the group, peaking at number 9. The single also peaked at number 25 on the [[Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles|''Billboard'' Bubbling Under Hot 100 Singles]], roughly equivalent to 125 on the main United States [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart. It also peaked at number 19 on the US [[Hot Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance Club Play]] chart. In the US, the song was released as a double [[A-side and B-side|A-side]] with \"[[A Red Letter Day]]\".\n\nThe Pet Shop Boys' version also uses elements of another ''West Side Story'' song, \"I Feel Pretty\", and the album version uses elements of \"One Hand, One Heart\" spoken by [[Chris Lowe]].\n\n===Track listings===\n;UK CD single 1 Parlophone CDRS 6470\n#\"Somewhere\"\n#\"The View from Yo